,"1449":"1449","Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands":"Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands","Princenhage, Brabant-septentrional, Pays-Bas":"Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dirven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Kirwan  . Now found chiefly in Lancashire, England."],"variants":[{"name":"Kirwan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donal, Brendan, Ronan.","Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ciardhubháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ciardhubhán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>ciar</i> ‘dark’ + <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + the diminutive suffix <i>-an</i>. This name and its variants are also found in Lancashire, England (see   Kirvan  ,   Kirven  ,   Kirvin  ,   Kirwin  ). Compare   Carawan  ."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356694,"age":40,"year":"1460","julianDay":2254314,"description":"The courtyard Episcopal palace at Atrecht had witch burnings.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356695,"age":57,"year":"1477","julianDay":2260524,"description":"Beginning of the rule of the Austrian Habsburgs.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter Jan Dirven was born about 1420, in Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands, his father, Jan Dirks Dirven, was 49 and his mother, Kathelijn Uten Ghoere, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Kathelijn Vos. He died in 1490, in his hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"about 1420–1490":"umbes 1420–1490","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1453–1500":"1453–1500","1372–1442":"1372–1442","1390–1449":"1390–1449","1500":"1500","1477":"1477","1442":"1442","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","1449":"1449","Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands":"Princenhage, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Princenhage, Brabant-septentrional, Pays-Bas":"Princenhage, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad"},"fi":{"about 1420–1490":"noin 1420–1490","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1453–1500":"1453–1500","1372–1442":"1372–1442","1390–1449":"1390–1449","1500":"1500","1477":"1477","1442":"1442","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","about 1420":"noin 1420","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","1449":"1449","Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands":"Princenhage, Noord-Brabant, Alankomaat","Princenhage, Brabant-septentrional, Pays-Bas":"Princenhage, Noord-Brabant, Alankomaat"},"fr":{"about 1420–1490":"environ 1420–1490","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1